# DMS BACKOFFICE APP RULES

This document contains comprehensive rules for developing and using the Data Migration Service (DMS) Backoffice App, a Jira Forge app with global screen UI designed to manage DMS migrations.

## Overview

The DMS Backoffice App is a Jira Forge app with a global screen UI designed to manage DMS migrations. It provides app owners with a centralized interface to register their apps for migration, monitor migration statuses, and manage access controls. The app enables seamless data migration from external sources to Forge Storage (KVS/SQL), allowing apps to become Level 4 applications within the Atlassian infrastructure.

## Product Definition

### Current Problem

Some of the Appfire Cloud Atlassian apps store customer or operational data externally, outside the Atlassian Cloud infrastructure. This limits their adoption of Atlassian Forge and prevents them from achieving the "Runs on Atlassian" (RoA) badge (Level 4 Forge Adoption).

**Edge Case:** An inactive tenant when the app was on level 3 or 2 might need to be migrated once the app is already on level 4. This process supports this edge case.

### Goals and Objectives

- Enable a seamless and transparent migration of external data into Forge Storage for customers
- Maintain a single version of the app capable of seamlessly working with either the previous external data source or Forge Storage, without the need to deploy a new version
- Allow apps to qualify as Level 4 Forge App and earn the RoA badge
- Ensure minimal disruption to customers and provide transparent migration status tracking to app teams

### Key Features

**Functional Requirements:**
- Automated migration workflow via Batch Processing Service (BPS) that pushes data to the app
- Support for KVS and SQL primarily. Support for Secret Storage and Entity Storage later if needed
- Migration readiness through a set of clear requirements
- Minimal app-side changes required. Platform provides a library with common parts
- Support for rollback ability that removes all records created on Forge Storage
- Migration triggered manually for individual tenant or predefined set of tenants via backoffice
- Comprehensive migration reporting and tracking via Migration Service Backoffice
- Scale seamlessly regardless of number of active tenants or complexity

**Non-Functional Requirements:**
- Monitor technical and business KPIs (TBD)
- Provide documentation and support to get app to "migration ready" state
- Provide documentation and support to implement and deploy migration stack for each app

**Key Features:**
- App registration for migration with user-provided App ID
- Migration stack ID validation (must end with "::forge-storage-migration")
- Access control management (users and groups)
- Migration status tracking (NOT_STARTED, IN_PROGRESS, COMPLETED, FAILED)
- Edit and delete functionality for registered apps
- Pagination for large app lists
- Professional UI with Atlassian Design System components
- Migration management for app installations across tenants
- Tenant installation filtering and bulk operations
- Migration status tracking and rollback capabilities

## Components

### Rule 0: DMS System Components

**The migration involves the following key components:**

**1. Batch Processing Service (BPS)**
- Centralized service orchestrating the migration process execution
- Includes data extraction, transformation, and loading into Forge Storage
- Completely transparent to app developers
- Belongs to Document Management Category
- Platform will integrate REST API with Auth Service
- Documentation available in internal repo (requires VPN access)

**2. Migration Stack (BPS Extension)**
- BPS client offering for migration integration:
  - **Tasks Integration Contracts**: Decouple migration logic from execution mechanism
  - **Migrations Job and Tasks base domain models**
  - **Producer and Consumer interfaces**
  - **Deployment Tooling**: AWS CDK Constructs, CLI tool
  - **REST API Client**: Public operations available in service

**App Developer Responsibilities:**
- Extend base migration domain model if required
- Implement producer and consumer interfaces
- Integrate client in pipeline to automate deployment to AWS account

**3. Migration Service Backoffice**
- Centralized interface for manually triggering migrations
- Individual tenant or predefined sets of tenants
- Comprehensive tracking and reporting by app and by app/tenant pair
- Essential for success of migration initiative

**4. "Migration Ready" Forge App**
- Version of app prepared to handle migration process
- Must meet migration readiness requirements
- Supports seamless data access via Forge Remote

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** understand all system components
- **MUST** implement Migration Stack (Producer and Consumer)
- **MUST** prepare app to be "Migration Ready"
- **MUST** use Migration Service Backoffice for migration management
- **SHOULD** understand BPS architecture and capabilities

## Requirements

### Rule 1: Service Dependencies

**Required Services:**

**1. Installation Service:**
- Provides tenant installation data
- Manages app installations across different Atlassian Cloud sites
- Essential for retrieving the list of active installations for registered apps
- Manages tenant-specific migration operations

**2. Token Repository Service:**
- Manages authentication tokens and credentials
- Required for secure communication between DMS Backoffice App and external services
- Ensures secure access to tenant data and migration operations

**3. Migration Service:**
- Core service that orchestrates data migration processes
- Requires a fully tested and deployed Migration Stack to be available for each registered app

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** integrate with Installation Service for tenant data
- **MUST** use Token Repository Service for authentication
- **MUST** ensure Migration Service is accessible
- **MUST** handle service unavailability gracefully
- **SHOULD** implement retry logic for service calls
- **MUST** handle authentication errors appropriately

### Rule 2: Migration Stack

**Definition:**
A Migration Stack is a predefined, tested configuration that defines how data should be migrated from external sources to Forge Storage (KVS/SQL).

**Migration Stack Requirements:**
- **MUST** be fully tested in a staging environment before registration
- **MUST** be deployed to the Migration Service before app registration
- **MUST** have stack ID ending with "::forge-storage-migration" to be valid
- **MUST** be registered within the Platform DMS service

**Stack ID Validation:**
```typescript
function isValidMigrationStackId(stackId: string): boolean {
  return stackId.endsWith('::forge-storage-migration');
}
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** validate migration stack ID format before registration
- **MUST** ensure migration stack is deployed and available
- **MUST NOT** allow registration with invalid stack ID format
- **SHOULD** verify stack availability before registration
- **MUST** provide clear error messages for invalid stack IDs

## Use Cases

### Rule 3: App Registration and Listing Feature

**Feature Description:**
Enables app owners to register their applications for data migration through the DMS Backoffice interface. Provides comprehensive validation, access control management, and status tracking capabilities.

**Feature: App Registration for Migration and Listing**
```
As an app owner
I want to register my app for migration in the DMS Backoffice
So that I can migrate my data from external sources to Forge Storage and become a Level 4 app
```

**Background:**
```
Given the DMS Backoffice App is installed and accessible as a Jira App
  And I have appropriate permissions to register apps for migration
  And the DMS service is running and accessible
  And the app to be migrated has the migration stack ready and registered within the Platform DMS service
  And I am viewing the DMS Backoffice global screen
```

**Scenario 1: Successfully register an app for migration**

**Description:** An app owner successfully registers their app for migration by providing all required information including App ID, Migration Stack ID, and access controls.

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am on the DMS Backoffice global screen
When I click the "Register App" button
Then I see the registration form with fields:
  | Field | Required | Type |
  | App Name | Yes | Text |
  | App ID | Yes | Text |
  | Migration Stack ID | Yes | Text |
  | Access Control (Users) | No | Multi-select |
  | Access Control (Groups) | No | Multi-select |

When I fill in the form:
  | Field | Value |
  | App Name | "My Awesome App" |
  | App ID | "com.example.myapp" |
  | Migration Stack ID | "my-stack::forge-storage-migration" |
  | Access Control (Users) | ["user1@example.com", "user2@example.com"] |
  | Access Control (Groups) | ["admin-group"] |

And I click the "Register" button
Then the app is successfully registered
And I see a success message: "App 'My Awesome App' has been registered for migration"
And the app appears in the registered apps list
And the migration status is "NOT_STARTED"
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** validate all required fields before submission
- **MUST** validate migration stack ID format
- **MUST** store app registration in persistent storage
- **MUST** display success message after registration
- **MUST** update app list immediately after registration
- **SHOULD** set initial migration status to NOT_STARTED

**Scenario 2: Validation error for invalid migration stack ID format**

**Description:** The system validates that the Migration Stack ID follows the required format ending with "::forge-storage-migration".

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am on the registration form
When I fill in the form:
  | Field | Value |
  | App Name | "My App" |
  | App ID | "com.example.app" |
  | Migration Stack ID | "invalid-stack-id" |

And I click the "Register" button
Then I see a validation error: "Migration Stack ID must end with '::forge-storage-migration'"
And the form is not submitted
And the app is not registered
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** validate migration stack ID format on form submission
- **MUST** display clear error message for invalid format
- **MUST NOT** allow submission with invalid stack ID
- **SHOULD** validate format in real-time as user types
- **MUST** highlight the invalid field

**Scenario 3: Validation error for missing required fields**

**Description:** The system validates that all required fields (App Name, App ID, Migration Stack ID) are provided before allowing registration.

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am on the registration form
When I leave required fields empty:
  | Field | Value |
  | App Name | "" |
  | App ID | "" |
  | Migration Stack ID | "" |

And I click the "Register" button
Then I see validation errors for all empty required fields:
  | Field | Error Message |
  | App Name | "App Name is required" |
  | App ID | "App ID is required" |
  | Migration Stack ID | "Migration Stack ID is required" |

And the form is not submitted
And the app is not registered
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** validate all required fields before submission
- **MUST** display field-specific error messages
- **MUST NOT** allow submission with missing required fields
- **SHOULD** validate fields in real-time
- **MUST** highlight fields with errors

**Scenario 4: View registered apps with different migration statuses**

**Description:** Users can view a list of registered apps with different migration statuses, filtered by their access permissions.

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am on the DMS Backoffice global screen
And there are registered apps with different statuses:
  | App Name | App ID | Status |
  | App A | "com.example.appa" | NOT_STARTED |
  | App B | "com.example.appb" | IN_PROGRESS |
  | App C | "com.example.appc" | COMPLETED |
  | App D | "com.example.appd" | FAILED |

When I view the registered apps list
Then I see all apps I have access to
And each app displays:
  | Field | Display |
  | App Name | Visible |
  | App ID | Visible |
  | Migration Stack ID | Visible |
  | Status | With status badge |
  | Actions | Edit, Delete buttons |

And apps are filtered by my access permissions
And I can see pagination controls if there are more than 10 apps
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** display all apps user has access to
- **MUST** show migration status with appropriate badges
- **MUST** implement pagination for large lists
- **MUST** filter apps by user permissions
- **SHOULD** sort apps by registration date (newest first)
- **MUST** display all required app information

**Scenario 6: Edit existing app registration**

**Description:** App owners can edit existing app registrations to update access controls while keeping App ID and Migration Stack ID immutable.

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am viewing the registered apps list
And there is an app "My Awesome App" registered
When I click the "Edit" button for "My Awesome App"
Then I see the edit form with:
  | Field | Editable | Current Value |
  | App Name | Yes | "My Awesome App" |
  | App ID | No | "com.example.myapp" |
  | Migration Stack ID | No | "my-stack::forge-storage-migration" |
  | Access Control (Users) | Yes | ["user1@example.com"] |
  | Access Control (Groups) | Yes | ["admin-group"] |

When I update:
  | Field | New Value |
  | App Name | "My Updated App" |
  | Access Control (Users) | ["user1@example.com", "user3@example.com"] |

And I click the "Save" button
Then the app registration is updated
And I see a success message: "App 'My Updated App' has been updated"
And the app list reflects the changes
And App ID and Migration Stack ID remain unchanged
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** allow editing of App Name and Access Controls
- **MUST NOT** allow editing of App ID and Migration Stack ID
- **MUST** display current values in edit form
- **MUST** validate updated data before saving
- **MUST** update storage after successful save
- **SHOULD** show confirmation before saving changes

**Scenario 7: Cancel edit app registration**

**Description:** Users can cancel the edit operation without saving changes, preserving the original app information.

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am editing app "My Awesome App"
And I have made changes to the form
When I click the "Cancel" button
Then the edit form is closed
And no changes are saved
And the app information remains unchanged
And I return to the apps list view
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** allow canceling edit operation
- **MUST NOT** save changes when canceled
- **MUST** preserve original app information
- **SHOULD** show confirmation if unsaved changes exist
- **MUST** return to apps list after cancel

**Scenario 8: Edit app registration with validation errors**

**Description:** The system validates form data during edit operations and prevents saving invalid information.

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am editing app "My Awesome App"
When I clear the App Name field
And I click the "Save" button
Then I see a validation error: "App Name is required"
And the form is not submitted
And the app information is not updated
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** validate form data during edit
- **MUST** display validation errors
- **MUST NOT** save invalid data
- **SHOULD** validate in real-time
- **MUST** highlight fields with errors

**Scenario 9: Change migration stack ID requires deletion and re-registration**

**Description:** When changing the Migration Stack ID, the app must be deleted and re-registered with the new stack ID, resulting in a new App ID.

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am viewing app "My Awesome App" with:
  | Field | Value |
  | App ID | "com.example.myapp" |
  | Migration Stack ID | "old-stack::forge-storage-migration" |

When I try to edit the Migration Stack ID
Then the Migration Stack ID field is disabled
And I see a message: "Migration Stack ID cannot be changed. Delete and re-register the app to use a different stack."

When I delete the app and re-register with:
  | Field | Value |
  | App Name | "My Awesome App" |
  | App ID | "com.example.myapp" |
  | Migration Stack ID | "new-stack::forge-storage-migration" |

Then the app is registered with a new App ID
And the old App ID is no longer associated with this app
```

**Requirements:**
- **MUST** disable Migration Stack ID field in edit mode
- **MUST** show message explaining why it cannot be changed
- **MUST** require deletion and re-registration to change stack ID
- **MUST** generate new App ID on re-registration
- **SHOULD** warn user about data implications of deletion

### Rule 4: Migration Management for App Installations Feature

**Feature Description:**
Enables app owners to manage migration status for their app installations across different tenants. Provides comprehensive tenant management, filtering capabilities, bulk operations, and migration status tracking with rollback functionality.

**Feature: Migration Management for App Installations**
```
As an app owner
I want to manage migration status for my app installations across different tenants
So that I can control which tenants are ready for migration and monitor the overall migration progress
```

**Background:**
```
Given the DMS Backoffice App is installed and accessible as a Jira App
  And I have appropriate permissions to manage app migrations
  And the DMS service is running and accessible
  And I have previously registered an app for migration
  And the app has installations across multiple tenants
  And the installation service provides the list of active installations for the app at registration time
  And I am viewing the DMS Backoffice global screen with the registered apps list
```

**Scenario 1: View tenant installations for a specific app**

**Description:** An app owner navigates to the tenant installations view to see all installations for their registered app with migration status overview.

**Gherkin Steps:**
```
Given I am viewing the registered apps list
And there is an app "My Awesome App" registered
When I click on "My Awesome App" or the "View Installations" button
Then I navigate to the tenant installations view
And I see a list of tenant installations:
  | Tenant | Installation ID | Cloud ID | Status | Actions |
  | appfire.atlassian.net | "ari:cloud:ecosystem::installation/inst-001" | "ari:cloud:ecosystem::site/cloud-001" | NOT_STARTED | Enable |
  | startup.atlassian.net | "ari:cloud:ecosystem::installation/inst-002" | "ari:cloud:ecosystem::site/cloud-002" | IN_PROGRESS | Details |
  | company.atlassian.net | "ari:cloud:ecosystem::installation/inst-003" | "ari:cloud:ecosystem::site/cloud-003" | COMPLETED | Details |
  | enterprise.atlassian.net | "ari:cloud:ecosystem::installation/inst-004" | "ari:cloud:ecosystem::site/cloud-004" | FAILED | Rollback, Details |

And I see migration statistics:
